This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it proposes a novel off-policy policy gradient method for Markov decision processes. It also involves policy evaluation and optimization, which are common topics in machine learning. Additionally, the paper may also fall under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it deals with improving the quality of policies discovered. The paper may also be relevant to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as it involves decision-making in dynamic environments. The system (cs.SY) sub-category may also be relevant as it involves control and optimization of systems. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category as it involves the estimation of state distributions.
